Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially hated it because he was responsible for waking up all the others in his squad. Quietly, he got up from his bunk, put on his combat suit, threw his body armor over, and retrieved his belongings from his locker, taking special care with a certain small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Hanging from it was everything he needed, like his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, the mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He took out a lighter from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short puff before slightly opening the door. In the last week, he had to come up with all sorts of ways to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset wake-up alarm, because it usually didn't work and all that came out of the speakers was a faint hiss.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Squad Leader Nemic approaching him.
„Yes," answered Cohren.
„What are you going to try this time?“
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith and a few others came toward him already in full uniform.
„Good morning," said Craith.
„What woke you up?“, asked Cohren.
„So, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you'd come up with today. And secondly, the vanguard, who are the first to rise, get to choose the morning ration," answered one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
„A good argument, Corporal," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm sounded in the barracks. Inside, he heard muttered curses and people running around in confusion.
„Come on, Valturi," said Nemic. „One would think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
„Well, my people from the training camp have learned," replied Cohren, pointing at Harris, Craith and Ravik. „However, the company and platoon commanders also know that they have to rise before their units."
Seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others rather annoyed.
„Good morning," said Cohren in a good mood.
„With all due respect, Sir, why do you have to wake us up so early?”, asked a staff sergeant from the assault troops.
„Because the regular alarms are terrible and because Daybreak doesn't sleep," said Cohren.
„Pack all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As lieutenant colonel and executive officer of the company, it was his responsibility to oversee and support them together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. „We are not coming back here. Staff sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second assault troop division, second army. Before they were consolidated, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren und Nemic, der Führer des ersten Zuges, gingen nebeneinander im Schein der vielen generatorbetriebenen Lampen der vorgeschobenen Einsatzbasis. Die meisten hatten rot getöntes Glas, um von feindlichen Bombern nicht entdeckt zu werden. Daybreak hatte auf Wild-Weasel-Angriffe aus der Luft und am Boden zurückgegriffen, um sie zu bekämpfen.
„Ein neuer Tag und eine neue Aufgabe für die Höllenhunde“, sagte Nemic mit einem trocken Lachen. „Wohin schicken sie uns?“
„Eine vorgeschowedene Einsatzbasis außerhalb von Ianlos. Wir werden den Bodenangriff unterstützen“, antwortete Cohren und zog an seiner Zigarette. Er gab Craith eine Teilschuld daran, dass er mit dem Rauchen angefangen hatte, aber ein Jahr im Einsatz veränderte einen, deshalb sagte er nichts.
„Scheiße. An der Front wird es immer schlimmer“, murmelte Nemic. „Alle Nachrichten lauten: «Unterstützt die Kriegsanstrengungen. Schickt Hilfe an die Kurgan-Front.» Wie wäre es mit Hilfe für die Howland-Front?“
„Amen, Bruder“, sagte Cohren und schnippte die Reste seiner Zigarette in den Schlamm. „Immerhin machen wir mit dem ersten bewaffneten Zug los und müssen nicht laufen. Hauptmann Shaw sollte schon da sein.“
“Shaw has offered us a ride?” Nemic asked a bit surprised.
“Yes. He's honestly not as bad as I thought. He's not particularly friendly, but you can put up with him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and adjusted his backpack at the same time. “All units of the Exodus Company will meet at the West Fleet Yard when they're ready. We'll depart with the first armed column at 0500.”
In the blink of an eye, he received responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all arrived here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren had the feeling he had known them forever, even though it had only been about two years. They were squad leaders, although Craith had been leading the second column for a week, after the previous leader had been relieved due to medical reasons following an assassination attempt by a Daybreak sharpshooter.
On the way to the Fleet Yard, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos combat tanks and four sniper tanks. Their crews were running around, making sure their machines were combat-ready. Quickly, Cohren spotted Major Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armed column. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came towards them as always with his expressionless face.
„Leutnant Nemic… Leutnant Valturi…“ He said Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren's holster for his pistols and then looked up again. „Do you think the company is ready?“
